Dealing with Blank values in Gender and OverTime

Replacing blank values with NAs

df$Gender[df$Gender==""]<- NA
df$OverTime[df$OverTime==""]<- NA

Converting Gender and OverTime to character type

Gender and OverTime variables will be converted to character type and then reconverted to factors to adjust the levels

df$Gender<-as.character(df$Gender)
df$OverTime<-as.character(df$OverTime)

Replacing the missing values of numerical variables by Mean Imputation

df$DistanceFromHome[is.na(df$DistanceFromHome)]<-mean(df$DistanceFromHome,na.rm = TRUE)
df$PercentSalaryHike[is.na(df$PercentSalaryHike)]<-mean(df$PercentSalaryHike,na.rm = TRUE)
df$TotalWorkingYears[is.na(df$TotalWorkingYears)]<-mean(df$TotalWorkingYears,na.rm = TRUE)
df$YearsSinceLastPromotion[is.na(df$YearsSinceLastPromotion)]<-mean(df$YearsSinceLastPromotion,na.rm = TRUE)

Replacing the missing values of categorical variables by kNN imputation

df <- knnImputation(df)

DISCRETIZATION

Loading dataframe into a new variable

data<-df

Function to discretize the attributes

breaks<-function(variable)
{
  discretize(variable, method = "frequency",breaks = 3, labels = c("low","medium", "high"))
}

Discretizing the attributes

for (i in c(1,4,6,11,17,18,19,21,25,28,29))
{
  data[,i]<-breaks(data[,i])
}

Function to discretize data with few datapoints

breaks2<-function(input)
{
  v<-input
  b<-quantile(input,c(0.25,0.75))
  v[input<=b[1]]<-"low"
  v[input>b[1] & input<b[2]]<-"medium"
  v[input>=b[2]]<-"high"
  v<-factor(v)
  return(v)
}

Discretizing the attributes

data$YearsSinceLastPromotion<-breaks2(data$YearsSinceLastPromotion)
data$YearsWithCurrManager<-breaks2(data$YearsWithCurrManager)

ASSOCIATION RULES USING APRIORI ALGORITHM

Converting the dataframe into a transactions matrix

ar<-as(data,'transactions')

Running the data through the algorithm to find rules when Attrition is Yes

rules<-apriori(ar,parameter = list(support=0.02,confidence=0.7,minlen=3,maxlen=15),appearance = list(default="lhs",rhs="Attrition=Yes"))

We can get the best rules by fine tuning the Hyper-parameters. There is no overfitting or underfitting because arules is unsupervised learning algorithm.
The rules displayed above are the most significant and interesting rules because of their higher lift values.
If the lift value is higher than 1, it lets us know the degree to which those two occurrences are dependent on one another, and makes those rules potentially useful for predicting the related target variable in the future datasets.
